, nearby abbeys were still the main focus of devotional activity; inquisitors' discoveries in the 1240s point to the previous twenty years as the period when Catharism and also the Waldensian heresy took a firm hold, most dramatically in its far north. This study deals with the cultural and political origins of the religious change. Its careful analysis offers a significant re-evaluation of the nature and social significance of religious dissidence,and of its protection and persecution in both the history and historiography of Catharism. Dr Claire Taylor is Associate Professor, School of History, University of Nottingham.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAlbigenseszFrancezQuercy. 0aChristian heresiesxHistoryyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aChristian heresieszFrancezQuercyxHistoryyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAlbigensian crusade.  aCathar heresy.  aLanguedoc.  aQuercy.  ahistoriography.  ahistory.  ainquisition.  amedieval county.  apersecution.  aprotection.  areligious dissidence.  asocial significance.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204011840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782040118423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782040118/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles